Former head of Brazilian presidential cabinet brought before court
On Tuesday, a federal judge accepted charges against the former head of the Brazilian presidential cabinet for his alleged involvement in a massive corruption scheme concerning the state oil company Petrobras.
The federal prosecutor's office said Jose Dirceu would be sued for corruption, scam and money laundering charges brought this month.
Fourteen other people will be tried, including Joao Vaccari Neto, the former treasurer of the Workers' Party, in power in Brazil, and Renato de Souza Duque, the former president of Petrobras's business services.
Dirceu is the oldest member of the ruling Workers' Party taken into custody for ties to the scheme.
Dirceu served as the cabinet chief of former President Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva between 2003 and 2005.
He was arrested in early August at home, where he was already under house arrest, with an 11-year sentence for involvement in a vote-buying scheme in Congress over 10 years ago.
Prosecutors said Dirceu developed the bribe-taking scheme at Petrobras, accepted bribes while in office and continued to receive payments from entrepreneurs after being jailed at the end of 2013 for the vote-buying scandal.
According to prosecutors, the Petrobras scheme involved about $2 billion in bribery and other illegal funds.
Some of that money would have returned to the campaign fund of the ruling party and their allies.
It would also have included bribes to Petrobras executives in exchange for inflated contracts.
"Miracle" recovery of a surviving student of the Peshawar massacre
A paralyzed teenager after being shot four times in Pakistan's worst terrorist attack managed a "miraculous" recovery after undergoing treatment in the United Kingdom.
13-year-old Mohamed Ibrahim Khan, the doctors in Pakistan had told him that he would never be able to walk again.
At least 140 people, mostly children, were killed when armed men attacked the army's public school in Peshawar last December.
Mohamed, who arrived in London last month for surgery, will later be discharged from the hospital.
Exactly nine months ago, on a regular Tuesday morning, Mohamed was sitting in first aid class and listening carefully to his teachers.
Just then, seven armed men disguised as security guards' uniforms were entering the army's public school.
They wore explosive belts and had a simple mission to accomplish: to kill all the men, women and children who came their way.
"I can't forget what happened that day," Mohamed says with a harsh look.
I was sitting in the auditorium, asking questions... then I heard gunshots outside.
The terrorists went inside and started killing. Our teacher was burned alive.
Mohamed describes how he removed four students from the amphitheater while the carnage was unfolding.
Then he says he heard his friend, Hamza, calling out to him.
He said, "oh, brother, save me."
I held his hand.
Then I was shot in the back, and he was shot in the head.
Most of those killed in the attack were students
Hamza died in Mohamed's arms.
Mohamed recalls that right after that he fainted and that the next thing he knew was that he was on a hospital bed, paralyzed from the waist down.
The doctors in Peshawar in northern Pakistan, then those in Rawalpindi, close to the capital, told his family that there was no treatment and that he would never be able to walk again.
"When I saw him, I felt my soul come out," says Sher Khan, Mohamed's father.
Those nine months were the hardest of my life.
But Khan and his wife, Sherbano, refused to believe that their son so fond of cricket would never be able to use his legs again.
They campaigned and sought help from Pakistani television, attracting the support of famous people such as Imran Khan, a cricketer turned politician.
Eventually, they were able to raise funds to take Mohamed to the United Kingdom and give him treatment at the private Harley Street clinic in London.
Consultant neurosurgeon Irfan Malik described Mohamed as "frightened" when he arrived at the hospital.
"He had spent the last [a few] months lying in bed, unable to move from side to side, Malik says.
He was weak, there was a lot of pressure on his back.
He wasn't in very good shape.
A vertebrae at the base of Mohamed's spine had been destroyed
Mohamed had been shot in the shoulder, hip and back during the attack, and his lower spine had been destroyed, leading to paralysis.
But during a six-hour operation, Malik and his team were able to retrace the nerve endings and rebuild the damaged part of the column.
Even Malik was surprised by what happened next.
Exactly a week after the surgery, Mohamed stood up and began to take steps and walk.
We didn't expect such a good result.
It was a miracle," he says.
Within two weeks of the operation, Mohamed is ready to leave the hospital and begin the long recovery process.
Mohamed defied fate and began to walk again
He wants to become strong and continue his studies in the United Kingdom.
But he is determined to return to Pakistan, join the army and fight terrorism.
"I feel like I still have a chance at life," he says, showing pictures of weapons drawn by him next to school textbooks and pens
Physically, Mohamed is getting stronger every day, but the psychological trauma he's going through and now it's unimaginable.
"My anger has not waned," he confesses.
Little children were killed in my school.
What crime did they commit?
His mother wipes out a tear, caresses the head and says, "I see my son walking again".
He will be able to go on with his life naturally.
