Steven Wilson: "If I do nothing, I feel guilty"
Steven Wilson has recently been named the big winner of the Progressive Music Awards
Steven Wilson has often been named as the most hardworking musician in the progressive rock world.
The talented musician won three awards at the Progressive Music Awards, which took place this month in London, including the award for Best Album of the Year for Hand.
In his five-star review, The Guardian called the album "an intelligent, expressive and captivating work of art".
Since the 1980s, Wilson has been the engine of several musical projects, the best known of which is the rock band Porcupine Tree.
Now, before two closed-house shows at Royal Albert Hall, Wilson releases a double LP in vinyl format only, Transience, to show the "more accessible" side of his solo work.
He told to the BBC about his love of vinyls and his busy schedule and explained how comedy actor Matt Berry got to open his performances.
What's vinyl to you?
I grew up in the very end of the vinyl era, and I remember that I couldn't wait for the CD to come out, because the vinyl was so annoying.
You'd buy a record, go home with him, have a scratch on him, and you'd have to bring him back.
I love CDs, and for certain types of music, like classical music, they're better than vinyl.
But the problem with CDs and digital downloads is that there is nothing left that you really value.
Having a vinyl is like having a beautiful painting hanging in your living room.
It's something you can hold in your hand, while you get absorbed in the lyrics and overwhelmed by the artistic act.
I thought it was just a nostalgic thing, but it can't be if some kids too young to remember vinyls like this kind of experience.
Do you have any vinyl you particularly care about?
I admit I got rid of all the vinyls in the '90s.
All the vinyls I have are bought again.
I started from the idea of redoing the collection I had when I was 15, but I crossed that line.
The first record I convinced my parents to buy me was Out of the Blue at the Electric Light Orchestra.
If I still had the original copy, it would have had sentimental value, but unfortunately, it is somewhere in a charity store.
Steven Wilson hopes the album will be a gateway to possible new fans
Why did you release your new Transience vinyl compilation?
This was originally conceived as an idea for record store day, but we missed the opportunity.
My label had suggested that I collect some of my shorter and more accessible songs.
I came to be easily obsessed with the idea of doing something like "introduction into Steven Wilson's music" and I absolutely wanted the project to be released on vinyl only.
Whoever buys vinyl also receives a downloaded variant at high resolution.
Are you worried that the album won't show your music in its true light?
No, because, although I focus on longer music pieces, there is one thing that I have always cherished above everything: the melodic side.
There is much progressive rock that focuses on technical complexity rather than the melodic side.
Pink Floyd, the most famous progressive rock band of all time, passed the test of time due to the fact that they always emphasized the melodic side and the atmosphere.
What are you preparing for the Albert Hall shows?
I don't want to reveal too much.
The repertoire will be completely different every one of the nights.
In the first, there will be a version of the show Hand. Erase. which we had this year, but on steroids, with a few guests.
The second night is going to be more of an incursion into my history, this being more oriented towards the fans who have been following me over the years.
How did you choose Matt Berry to open your show on the second night?
And me and the others on the tour team are big fans of [the Channel 4 comedy series] Toast of London, to the point where we always give quotes from it.
I thought I'd listen to Matt's music, too, so I bought him the album, Music for Insomniacs.
I talked to him about our mutual love for Mike Oldfield and asked him to sing at the Royal Albert Hall.
It seems to me I'm extremely lucky to have him in the open.
You remixed albums by bands like XTC, Tears for Fears and Yes.
How much does that affect your own music?
I do not consciously inspire myself from this, but inevitably, when you deconstruct these classic albums, they remain in your mind.
My last solo album, The Raven That Refused to Sing, was undoubtedly the most progressive old school album I ever created.
I don't think it was a coincidence that we had remixed King Crimson, Jethro Tull and Yes almost all of the previous year.
The current album, Hand. Erase., is much more open, because I had worked at Tears for Fears and XTC.
You are often described as the busiest progressive rock musician.
Is that how you feel?
You can eliminate the progressive word.
I think I'm probably one of the most labor-obsessed people in the music world today, and I'm not saying this proudly, because, please believe me, it's a curse.
I think I inherited this from my father, who has an incredibly strong work ethic.
If I don't do anything for a whole day, I'm starting to feel guilty.
That's why working on remixes was a gift, because it means I don't always have to do just my music.
The music industry is a tough place to make a career.
Now I wouldn't recommend that to anyone as a profession.
I work daily and am not rich, but I live well.
I love what I do, it's a privilege, but if I were lazy, I don't think I would have survived.
Transience will be released in the United Kingdom on 25 September.
Steven Wilson will perform at the Royal Albert Hall on 28 and 29 September, as part of his 2015-2016 European tour.
