A new study shows that more people die from air pollution than from malaria and HIV/AIDS
According to a new reference study, more than 3 million people per year die prematurely from external air pollution, more than malaria and HIV/AIDS together.
The main cause, especially in Asia, is burning wood and coal for heating homes and cooking, but research reveals that an equally alarming reason is agricultural emissions from Europe and the US, where they are the main reason for these deaths.
The report warns that unless action is taken, the death toll - already equivalent to six deaths per minute - will double by 2050.
"These projections should sound an alarm for public health agencies around the world," said Professor Michael Jerrett, an environmental health expert, at the University of California, who was not involved in research.
Most of the deaths caused by air rain are caused by tiny particles, which can be inhaled deep into the lungs.
They cause heart attack and stroke, which are responsible for three-fourths of the 3.3 million deaths annually, while the rest are caused by lung cancer and respiratory disease.
Research did not include the effects of indoor air pollution, for example from cooking fires, which is estimated to cause an additional 3.4 million deaths per year.
The new study, published in the Nature newspaper, is the first to highlight various sources of external air pollution and estimated the number of premature deaths they cause, taking into account road traffic, fossil fuel plants and other sources.
Researchers have used a detailed computer model of the global atmosphere, to assess the impact of air pollution on various populations, including new information on how pollution affects the inhabitants of China and India.
One third of all premature deaths were the result of the use of smoke-extinguishing fuels such as wood and coal, for home heating or cooking, and the use of dirty diesel generators for electricity, all of which were recognized hazards.
The consumption of this type of internal energy causes half of India's 645,000 annual deaths and one third of China's 1.4 million annual deaths.
But research found that agricultural ammonia emissions had a "remarkable" impact, according to Professor Jos Leveld of the Max Planck Chemical Institute in Germany, who led the research.
One-fifth of global deaths are caused by these emissions, mainly from cattle, birds and pigs and overuse of fertilisers.
Ammonia reacts with exhaust gases from traffic and industry and produces tiny particles, being the main cause of death due to air pollution in the eastern US, Japan and Europe.
"For London, agriculture is the main source," says Lelieveld.
Throughout the United Kingdom, 48% of premature deaths were the result of agricultural pollution.
Traffic pollution is still an important factor in developed countries, causing one-fifth of the dead despite measures against polluting vehicles.
It caused only 5% of deaths globally, but the figure could increase as more cars appear on the streets in developing countries.
Air pollution by plants, especially those operating on coal, was significant globally, causing one in seven deaths.
In the US it is the single main factor, causing one third of the 55 000 deaths annually, compared to 16% in the United Kingdom.
Natural air pollution, especially in arid and dusty regions, caused nearly one fifth of the deaths globally caused by air pollution.
This source is a major factor in some arid countries, responsible for 92% of the deaths in Egypt and 81% in Iran.
"The overlapping between the high degree of pollution and the large number of residents says their word on public health, but there is little known about the sources of pollution responsible for premature deaths," Jerrett says.
The results are surprising and potentially important for the protection of public health at global level.
At present it is assumed that all particles are equally toxic.
But if those caused by fuel burning are more toxic, as some scientists suspect, the percentage of premature deaths attributable to agricultural emissions would be lower.
Even so, Jerrett says "the discovery is very valuable... because agriculture has not generally been seen as a major source of air pollution or premature death and because it suggests that much more attention must be paid to agricultural sources, both from scientists and political leaders".
Dr. Oliver Wild, an atmosphere specialist at Lancaster University in the United Kingdom said, "The study does underline the need for air quality control, to avoid these deaths, especially in highly populated areas of Asia".
