Coral reefs are subject to serious decline risks (WWF) Some marine habitats, such as mangroves and seagrass, on which many other species depend, have experienced a significant decline, while entire populations of commercially valuable fish, such as mackerel and tuna, have plummeted by three quarters since the 1970s, the report says.
Many coral reefs, usually described as ocean rainforests due to their huge biodiversity, could be threatened with extinction by the middle of this century if ocean acidity continues to worsen, as a result of increased CO2 levels in the atmosphere, causing a directly proportional increase in carbonic acid levels in the sea.
"Healthy seas are a source of extraordinary natural beauty and astonishment and are also a basis for the functioning of the global economy," said Louise Heaps, chief adviser on marine policies at WWF-UK, who contributed to the report.
"By overfishing, which damages coastal habitats, and without solving the problem of global warming, we sow the seeds of an ecological economic catastrophe," Dr. Heaps says.
The report, based on a review of published scientific literature, but also on the Living Planet Index, a database maintained by the Zoological Society of London, is one of the most detailed studies on marine life ever undertaken.
Nearly 20% of all mangrove areas disappeared between 1980 and 2005 (WWF) It researched a great diversity of marine species, from fish, sea turtles and sea cucumbers - a worm-like animal, with rough skin - to marine plants such as mangroves and algae.
The report found that algae areas had decreased by about 30% in the last century, while total mangrove areas decreased by 20% between 1980 and 2005, mainly as a result of shrimp fishing and other forms of aquaculture.
Over a single generation, human activity has caused huge damage to the ocean, catching fish faster than it can reproduce and also destroying their shoals.
Deep changes are needed to ensure abundant ocean life in the next generations," said Marco Lambertini, general director of WWF International.
Some of the most dramatic declines occurred in species fished for commercial profits.
For example, 58 populations from 17 species belonging to the family Scrombidae - mackerel, tuna and sardines - decreased by 74% between 1970 and 2010, with no signs of recovery, the report says.
We are in a fishing race that could end with people being deprived of a vital food source and an essential economic engine.
Overfishing, destruction of marine habitats and climate change have serious consequences for the entire human population, and poor communities, which rely on the sea, will be hit the fastest and strongest," Lambertini said.
"The collapse of ocean ecosystems could trigger a serious economic decline and undermine our struggle to eradicate poverty and malnutrition," he continued.
Professor Ken Norris, scientific director of the ZL, said, "These alarming figures prove how quickly humans change plants and animals in the oceans and represent a clear warning about the problems we might face as a result".
Seagrass: sprawling submarine "grass", which catches mineral-rich sediments and stabilizes the seabed.
Over the last century, the surface area has decreased by 30%.
Mangrove: their existence is known in 123 countries, with almost half of the total area representing only five countries.
Nearly 20% of all mangrove areas disappeared between 1980 and 2005, mainly due to human invasion.
Coral reefs: some of the richest and most biologically productive habitats on earth.
A quarter of all marine species live in or near coral reefs, but three-fourths of these are currently under threat and many may disappear over the course of this century if the acidity of the ocean continues to worsen.
Habitats in the deep: very little is known about the deeper areas of the ocean, but the decline in the amount of fish caught in these inaccessible locations over the last 40 years suggests that they are also affected by global marine change.
