Three new studies so that the administration of antidepressants to pregnant women has no effect on the neural or behavioural development of their children.
Studies have shown that selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) are at increased risk of postpartum bleeding, but researchers have said that depression is an even greater risk for women and their children, therefore it should be treated.
"These studies add to an increasing set of evidence regarding the safety of antidepressant administration during pregnancy," said in a press release John Thorp, deputy editor-in-chief of the International Journal of Obstetrics and Gynecology, who published all three studies.
Although there are some increased risks, so far the evidence appears to show that the risks of untreated depression are greater than those raised by antidepressants.
The Norwegian Institute for Public Health coordinated a study on motor development of children whose mothers treated themselves with SSRI, analyzing data of 51 404 children from the Norwegian Mother and Child Cohort Study, researching the effects of using SSRI for motor skill development at the age of 3.
Researchers discovered that 381 mothers had used SSRI during pregnancy, and 159 of them were treated with drugs for a prolonged period.
Although exposure to SSRI was associated to some extent with a delay in motor development, researchers wrote in the study that the association "was not so significant as to attach clinical importance to the delay".
A group of researchers at Adelaide University in Australia conducted a data examination for 49,000 women in the Danish National Birth Cohort to discover the effects of SSRI administration on children's behaviour by the age of 7.
The study found that untreated depression in pregnant women was associated with an increased risk of behavioral problems.
In 210 children whose mothers had been treated against depression with SSRI there was no increased risk of behavioral problems compared to the 231 children who were more prone to behavioral problems such as hyperactivity, lack of attention and social problems.
The same group of Australian researchers also discovered in a separate study, that mothers are more prone to bleeding after birth if treated with SSRI.
Analysis of medical data from 30 198 who gave birth at an Adelaide university hospital between 2002 and 2008 showed that the risk of postnatal haemorrhage increased by 5%, between 11 and 16%, if women were treated with SSRI.
The risk of severe bleeding or postnatal anaemia has doubled, researchers reported.
Researchers have said that although the study linked the administration of SSRIs at increased risk, there are a large number of variables - from medicines taken during birth to the limited amount of information the researchers had about specific medical conditions of women - that could have had an effect on bleeding potential.
"Women who have taken antidepressants at an advanced stage of pregnancy may have been those with the worst stage of the disease, and this is the reason for the increased risk of postnatal haemorrhage, not antidepressants," says Dr. Luke Grzeskowiak, a professor at Adelaide University.
On the basis of this study alone, we do not recommend that women stop their drug treatment against depression during pregnancy, but be closely monitored to reduce as much as possible the risk of potential bleeding.
