At the beginning of the school year
Yesterday, my eldest son, Stephen, started school.
The preparatory class, as he tries to improve the situation.
I don't know whether to enjoy or let myself be overwhelmed by melancholy; I am leaning, passively, towards the second variant.
First of all, because I get the feeling that it's only been three weeks, not three years since I took him to kindergarten for the first time, with emotions.
Although he breathes relievedly, no normal parent enjoys raising his children.
Secondly, because I remember perfectly the same day from my childhood; then began a story that, at the very least, did not end until today.
I wasn't even what's usually called a conscientious student.
On the contrary, I would say.
But school always liked me.
So much so that I chose to continue to attend it, even if as a teacher.
When I decided that's what I wanted to do my whole life, I knew it wasn't an easy job.
And none with any stakes.
That is because, like all of us, I have come across all sorts of teachers: better or worse, nicer or unbearable, smarter or downright imbeciles.
It happens, unfortunately, that there are people with other calls in this guild.
I think they're toxic, because they hurt the enthusiasm and even the mind of a young man willing to form.
I was fortunate to give, while I was a student or student, over a few, few, exceptional teachers.
These meetings can be decisive if they are at the right time.
Who thinks that the role of the department is the banal transmission of some information is sadly mistaken.
That can be done by anyone; to be informed, one can inform the student very well on his own, that we are just living in the era of transparency.
A good teacher, however, shapes the minds of alumns.
It forms them, it creates their thinking.
Sitting in the chair is not a privilege, as many believe, but a great responsibility.
Young people are very picky, demanding, unforgiving and always willing to look for the flaws of those in front of them.
That's how their age dictates their temper.
As a teenager, we all thought we knew everything, that we had unwavering certainties about everything.
When we grow up, we come to understand that we have only doubts.
Therefore, the role of a teacher is to pull the teenager out of his categorical self-sufficiency and make him think.
That is, to learn to doubt, to ask questions.
To discover on their own the answers, be they provisional.
To get involved in everything he does.
Lead him discreetly to profitable models.
It's very difficult, especially since most of the time the student thinks the teacher is his enemy.
One who can't wait to catch him on the wrong foot to sanction him.
However, this entitles him, the always misunderstood, rebellious, to live to the fullest of his age calls, to regard the one at the department with suspicion.
He can't just naturally accept his attempt to order it.
Teenagers do not allow themselves to be put in place, do not accept restrictions.
Or if they give the impression they're doing it, they're getting revenge somehow.
And unfortunately, when there is a rigid person in the department, who imposes himself by hardness and does not communicate, the students take their revenge on the object taught.
There are thousands of such teenagers who miss meetings with great writers, for example, because of the lack of tact of the Romanian teacher.
There are thousands of such students who have the impression that history is a sequence of data, that mathematics are all that can be more exhausting to their unripe minds.
I always urge my students: if you come across a teacher you don't swallow, who doesn't know how to communicate human to human with you, don't let him push you away from the literature to which he should direct you.
How did it happen that I became a teacher myself?
I had a really good teacher in grades VI-VIII.
He opened my mind to some texts that spoke to the puber then on his own understanding.
I met, in high school, a university professor who opened the door to his library.
I looked at him as a man from another world: he had the walls of the house covered with bookshelves.
I got lost in his library and dreamed of having one of those.
Now maybe I have it, but if fate hadn't gotten in my way, maybe I'd have decided to become a football player.
Or an engineer or a lawyer or something.
I don't think meetings like this are random.
I don't believe in chance.
The main thing is to run into the man who takes your hand and patiently directs you to your own vocation.
And this is, most of the time, the teacher.
Now, my experience only helps me talk about what it means to teach literature.
It's just that literature can't be taught.
There is no teacher of literature, as there is a teacher of mathematics.
How to fix the ineffable in concepts?
You can, at most, approximate it, without the claim that you convey petrified truths.
The one in the department can at best guide reading, that's something else.
But it can especially occasion miraculous encounters between a reader and books.
There are meetings that can change the life of the bank.
There are meetings that can open his mind, that can lift someone's words, the scales on his eyes.
That is why the literature teacher must, first of all, manage to make his students understand (feel) that there is no divorce between literature and life.
On the contrary!
A great coseur, Al. Paleologu, said one thing only apparently paradoxical: "How much literature, so much life, not the other way around!" and was right.
That is why a good teacher prepares you for life, does not make you a specialist in an open field anyway.
Fortunately, we always have to learn something.
And we, the teachers; or especially we, the teachers.
Most of the time, a great truth is repeated only out of inertia: not only do the disciples learn from their masters, but also the other way around.
Ideally, the teacher should be a master, and the student an apprentice.
Who, like any valuable young man, leaves his master when he discovers his own path.
Few find him, that's right.
But it was the master who ignited the spark.
I do not believe that there is greater happiness for a pure blood teacher than that of enduring as many such breakups as possible.
