Expanding investigation to FIFA
Justice in the US and Switzerland will proceed to new arrests
US and Swiss authorities have announced they will start prosecutions of new people and organisations as part of the FIFA corruption investigation, international media reports.
US Justice Minister Loretta Lynch announced in a press conference in Zurich on Monday that the area of investigations into corruption in world football had been widened.
"On the basis of our co-operation and on the basis of new evidence, we will commit further criminal prosecutions against new individuals and new organisations," Lynch said.
In May, several FIFA senior officials were arrested in Switzerland in this corruption case.
Many of them have already been extradited to the US.
"We have hopes that other people prosecuted will reach the US as well," Lynch added.
Switzerland's Attorney General Michael Lauber, also present at the press conference, said his institution had seized several goods, including housing and land in the Alps, as well as financial assets, as part of the investigation conducted in collaboration with the US.
"We haven't reached the end of the first half either," Lauber said.
So far, a very large amount of information has been seized, 11 terrabytes.
At the same time, 121 bank accounts are being investigated.
A contract to cede media rights to investigators also came to the 2010 World Cups in South Africa and in 2014 - Brazil.
FIFA faces a big corruption scandal, after US justice indicted 14 people, including two FIFA vice presidents and seven forum officials.
Detained persons are being investigated for bribery and receiving other benefits, from the early 1990s until now, totaling over $150 million.
Following this scandal, Swiss Joseph Blatter announced, in early July, that he was resigning as FIFA president, after being re-elected for the fifth time.
