A Syrian artist turned "Super Mario" into a refugee
A Syrian artist created a refugee version of the popular game "Super Mario", which evokes the plight of his compatriots, on their way to Europe.
Instead of presenting the adventures of Italian plumber Mario in the Kingdom of Mushrooms, the modified video game has "Mario Refugee" at its center.
The character tries to get past human traffickers and border police, on his way to a refugee centre in the European Union.
The Istanbul-based artist uses the pseudonym Samir al-Mufti for security reasons and said he made the video game with refugee Mario after his friends ventured on a dangerous trip to Europe, to escape the horrors of war.
At Craiova Detention Center the youngest student is 15 years old and is in the first class
Justice Minister Robert Cazanciuc said, at the opening of the school year at Craiova Detention Center, that the youngest student is 15 years old and is in the first grade, and the oldest one is 25 years old and is in the 11th grade, showing that they could have another life if they went to school.
I chose to participate in the opening of the school year in a center belonging to the National Administration of Prisons to try to draw attention, and in this way, to lesser known realities.
The youngest student, aged 15, is enrolled in the first grade, and the oldest is 25 years old and is enrolled in the 11th grade.
"There are complicated topics that society is concerned about debating at the moment, we are all pressed by our own worries and problems, but we must not overlook the lesson that these more than 100 young people from Craiova Detention Center offer," Minister Robert Cazanciuc said at the opening ceremony of the school year on Monday.
The Minister of Justice pointed out that the lack of education, motivated in many cases by the lack of material possibilities, can lead to tragedies, stating that the young people in this centre would have had another chance in life if they could have followed the natural school course of any child, if they had the opportunity to learn not only to write, to read, but also to receive a set of moral values, to find out what compliance with the law means and what consequences it may have.
"The role of the prison system is not to permanently isolate from society people who have broken the law, to close them behind high walls, but to try to re-educate them and prepare them, so that when they return to the community they have more chances of reintegration," Cazanciuc added.
The minister noted that it is necessary to invest in schools, hospitals, roads, but investments must also be made in the prison system, because in many cases the conditions of detention are borderline to humanity and because, in the absence of money and staff, it will be difficult to talk about the reintegration of convicted persons.
We collaborate very well with the Ministry of Education and thanks to this partnership, every year, in the prison system, there are over 2000 graduates of the school education courses.
Obviously, we will not be able to change overnight that has not been done for 25 years, but these are important steps that we are taking.
"In all these actions we also need the support of society, and this support can only come if we demonstrate that we are doing our duty, that through your work these young people have a chance and are not a danger to society," said Cazanciuc.
The Minister of Justice wished both students and educators success, showing that success comes only through the conjugated effort of all.
"And because today is the celebration of the Ascension of the Holy Cross, I would launch to all students and teachers the invitation to visit the mausoleums of Soveja, Marăşti and beyond, in order to understand what the struggle of young people for ideals means," said Robert Cazanciuc.
