Now, however, we can refer to procedures: we have seen a democratic exercise of an impressive scale.
British Labour did not invent the system of direct voting for the party leader, among the Western left.
The French Socialists have been practicing for several years a more complicated, motion-based system that allows for the expression of all members and sympathizers; in addition, they have held a preliminary competition for the nomination of the presidential candidate since 2012.
However, the internal Labour vote seems more spectacular and politically significant, as the newly elected leader automatically becomes its spearhead in the upcoming elections.
It is, of course, also a matter of political system, with the customization of power being more pronounced in Britain than on the other side of the English Channel.
In addition, turnout was high in all three "circles": members themselves, members of unions and other organizations affiliated with the party and, finally, the group of sympathizers (who received the ballot after a summary registration procedure).
This last group gives us interesting information about the perceptions of left-wing segments in British society, especially those made up of young or middle-aged people, educated, interested in the political phenomenon.
Many of them will choose to become even more involved, in the future, precisely because of the signal provided by Corbyn's victory.
There are, as far as I know, no sociological inquiries that tell us too much about the attitudes of this "outer circle" Labour, so cautious speculation is allowed.
I think we are seeing enough attitudes similar to those of Podemos sympathizers (Spain) or even SYRIZA (Greece), with the observation that they will go through the traditional channels of the left.
If we want to identify an "antisystem" vocation, it is reflected primarily by the rejection of the centrist line, New Labour (for many, only a disguised form of the much-hulled thatcherism).
The second component would be the repudiation of leaders deemed guilty of the two successive election failures, one argument being that they did not go enough to the left, that they did not firmly delineate from the Tony Blair era.
The second landmark - after me, and more suggestively - is offered by the recent referendum on Scotland's independence.
If we abstract the separatist message and focus strictly on aspirations on other political topics, we see how Scottish nationalists have captured the energies of public segments favorable to the social state and animated by the aspiration of equity, adept at disarmament and hostile to military involvement abroad, but also sensitive to the new themes of the left: ecology, gender, assistance for poor countries.
Scottish Labour thus lost an electorate to which they should have, at least in principle, had privileged access, but which they can now recover (see their enthusiasm for Corbyn's campaign).
Such energies exist all over the United Kingdom, but the old leadership has not been able to attract them.
Jeremy Corbyn, with his vocation as an outsider, has more chances of success than Ed Miliband, the Labour "aristocrat".
The comparison with Scotland tells us more, I think, than the one with the anti-system left in the southern periphery of Europe.
The term "antisystem" is too harsh: "anti-establishment" seems more appropriate to me.
By next week we will know more about Jeremy Corbyn's first steps, as leader of the opposition.
We will see if the Red Flag will also ring in the House of Commons (it would not be the first time), after the new leader has taken his seat, primarily of the opposition banks.
However, what Jeremy Corbyn now wants from his colleagues in Parliament is primarily unity - and in this regard he does have reason to be concerned.
