While writing the article it occurred to me to check the online story of the former fighter and "Syrian rebel commander Laith Al-Saleh" became in the second part of the space dedicated by V. Marin to his person "jihadist Laith Al-Saleh" (the two categorizations - "rebel" and "jihadist" - could itself make me from the beginning circumspect).
I didn't.
In last week's article (Europe, between refugees and "refugees") we commented in parallel two pictures - the one with little Aylan Kurdi found dead on the Mediterranean shore and the one, in fact: the two depicting Syrian Laith Al-Saleh once as a fighter, the second time as a refugee.
The story of Laith Al-Saleh was taken from the article "Syrian Fighters Come with the Wave of Refugees" (signed by Viorica Marin in The Truth of 3 September).
Monday night, I posted a link to my article on my Facebook page.
On Tuesday, going on Facebook, I found, among other things, a sleeve pull from the friend (not just the FB) Marius Cristian: "I subscribe, only a statement. Laith al Saleh is not a jihadist".
On the contrary, he's a fighter against Al Assad, for democracy and all that.
"So you could have added rude manipulation to the painting"!
I have to admit, I felt terrible.
All the more so as I wrote the article it occurred to me to check on the net the story of the former fighter and "Syrian rebel commander Laith Al-Saleh" became in the second part of the space dedicated by V. Marin to his person "jihadist Laith Al-Saleh" (the two categories - "rebel" and "jihadist" - could in itself make me circumspect).
Because I trusted the truth, his journalists.
On the spot, I had no further comment on Marius Cristian's sleeve pull than that: "That's what I need if I trusted the Truth"
After that, I obviously took the story for small money and I feel indebted to readers with the correct presentation of the story of Syrian Laith Al-Saleh.
The oldest I found in an Associated Press (Syrian rebel leader seeks Europe - Syrian rebel leader seeks Europe) material signed by Nicholas Baphitis and Dalton Bennett from 17 August 2015 on the island of Kos in Greece, where thousands of refugees, perhaps, noticed a man trying to tidy up in the chaos of the crowd, among the hundreds.
The man was Syrian stucco Laith Al Saleh of Aleppo who "is accustomed to being in command", since he "led a unit of 700 rebels in the civil war in Syria".
We also learn that Al Saleh, 30, had had "a home, a wife and a normal life before the fight that cost more than 250,000 lives and put a third of Syria's population on the road".
In the interview with Associated Press correspondents, Al Saleh tells that "everyone wants to leave Syria".
My city is the most dangerous city in the world.
About 70% of the city is destroyed.
In Syria, Al Qaeda wants me, Daesh (an extremist group of the Islamic State) wants me, the government wants me - I fought against everyone.
Beyond being kicked out of a supermarket on the island, Kos would have offered him "an even more sinister encounter - with a man in whom he recognized a Syrian enemy": "Two days ago, I saw a sniper from government forces".
I haven't talked to him, but I'm still very upset.
From the material we also learn that Laith (which means lion in Arabic) was, indeed, on his way to Holland, where he has a cousin - former senior officer in the Syrian army and then he too became a rebel and arrived in the West after being seriously wounded - hoping to obtain asylum and then be able to bring his family - his wife and a three-year-old boy (nearly at an age with the civil war in Syria, which broke out in March 2011).
After this had succeeded, Laith Al-Saleh would not have ruled out a return to Syria to continue the fight for the Syrian Free Army (supported by the West) - against three forces: the army of President Bashar Assad (supported by the Russians), the Islamic State and the Al-Qaeda-affiliated Nusra Front.
Madness - whoever wants freedom must fight in Syria against not one enemy but three!
I also came across a Serbian material from 22 August, of which I didn't understand much, except that Laith Al Saleh is associated with terrorists who come with migrants: TERRORISTI SE KRIJU MEĐU MIGRANTIMA sounds the title of a newscast on http://www.telegraf.rs/vesti, in which a picture of Al Saleh with a beard holding a Syrian flag and that of a refugee in which he wears the "THANK YOU" shirt.
On 7 September, then, himself on the BBC website, Mike Wendling drew attention to the case of manipulation with the help of pictures of the Syrian fighter: This viral photo falsely claims to show an IS fighter posing as a refugee - This viral picture misrepresents a fighter of the Islamic State posing as a refugee.
We find out that the picture (in fact: the pictures - the one with the beard and the gun and the one with the THANK YOU shirt) was posted by a user on Facebook, who would also have apologized in the meantime.
Only before that, just off his wall, the picture of the two pictures would have been shapped over 70,000 times, gathering several thousand comments.
That talk, too late, the horse was gone!
In Romania, on 9 September Carla Dinu of Hotnews takes over the story of manipulation on the BBC, but mistranslating the title: "A fake photo turned viral shows an ISIS fighter posing as a refugee".
Obviously, it's not the photo that's fake, it's the interpretation that was false, wrong, in short: manipulative.
